<p><b>Human Rights Council 
Eleventh session 
</b>Agenda item 3 
<b>Promotion and protection of all human rights, civil, political, economic,  
social and cultural rights, including the right to development 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Report of the Special Rapporteur on the independence of 
judges and lawyers, Leandro Despouy</b>*<b> 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Addendum 
</b></p>
<p><b>  Mission to Guatemala</b>**<b> 
</b></p>
<p> <i>Summary</i> 
 The Special Rapporteur on the independence of judges and lawyers, Leandro 
Despouy, conducted a visit to Guatemala from 26 to 30 January 2009 at the invitation of 
the Government. The Special Rapporteur observed that the prevalence of impunity in 
Guatemala has a number of causes, the main ones being a variety of structural factors and 
the violence to which justice professionals are subjected. Despite the efforts that have been 
made, urgent reforms are needed. 
</p>
<p> In the first place, a unified justice policy has to be established. Currently, there are 
many different institutions acting in a fragmentary and disjointed manner, which has a 
negative impact on the work of the justice system as a whole. It is particularly necessary to 
define a State criminal and criminological policy. The establishment of a Ministry of 
Justice could help to solve these problems. 
</p>
<p> At the same time, it is necessary to regulate the way in which justice officials are 
elected. The existing system is open to external interference and is highly politicized, and 
this has a negative impact on the independence of the judiciary. 
</p>
<p>  
</p>
<p> * This report was submitted late because of limited publishing capacity. 
 ** The summary of this document is being circulated in all official languages. The full report, which is 
</p>
<p>contained in the annex to the summary, is being circulated in the language of submission only. 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
